Prosper Loan Data Analysis¶

by Mohammed Elshafei¶

This data set contains information on peer to peer loans facilitated by credit company Prosper. The data set contains 113,937 loans with 81 variables on each loan, including loan amount, borrower rate (or interest rate), current loan status, borrower income, and many others.

As we can see, the dataset contains 81 columns which will be complex to analyize all of this data. So, for the purpose of this analysis we will look into the following variables:

  • Term
  • LoanStatus
  • BorrowerRate
  • ProsperRating (Alpha)
  • ListingCategory (numeric)
  • EmploymentStatus
  • CreditScoreRangeLower
  • CreditScoreRangeUpper
  • TotalProsperLoans
  • LoanOriginationDate
  • ProsperScore

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

Following some data wrangling techniques, we reached to 84,853 listings for loan via peer-to-peer credit company Prosper. The variables we have selected are numeric, categorical and datetime types.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

In this investigation, i will try to know what that factors lead to defaulting on loans.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

I believe that the employment status & credit score will impact the loan status.

we can see that there is rating of 11.0 which is contradicting with the definitions in the dictionary of this data set this maybe due to wrong typo error. Hence we will change the value of 11.0 to 10.0.

In [25]:
# Define function to change scoring
def change_rating(row):
    if row['ProsperScore'] == 11.0:
        return 10.0
    else:
        return row['ProsperScore']
In [26]:
#Replace 11.0 score with 10.0 score
analysis_df['ProsperScore'] = analysis_df.apply(change_rating, axis=1)

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

Prosper ratings was normally distributed. The disrubution of average credit scores was sckewed right. Also, the ProsperScore was strange to see that the rating 4.0 was the highest amongst the ratings. I did not beleive that any transformation is useful here.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

I thought that the credit score distribution should have been normally distributed. I have performed some operations to tidy the data where i dropped some null values and changed the data for LoanOriginationDate to datetime format. Also, changed the prosperscore 11.0 to 10.0 as the dictionary was stated that scores was from 1.0 to 10.0.

In the next steps we will remove the current status loans where they are not our focus in this analysis as we are investigating the outcomes of the loan which is completed or defaulted.

# define function to set chargedoff as defaulted
def change_status(row):
    if row['LoanStatus'] == 'Chargedoff':
        return 'Defaulted'
    else:
        return row['LoanStatus']

Credit Score with Loan Status

for this analyis we need to bin the credit scores for easy visualization

In [38]:
#define function
def bin_creditscore(row):
    score = row['AverageCreditScore']
    if  score < 650:
        return 'up to 649'
    elif score < 700:
        return 'between 650 and 699'
    elif score < 750:
        return 'between 700 and 749'
    elif score < 800:
        return 'between 750 and 799'
    elif score < 850:
        return 'between 800 and 849'
    elif score < 900:
        return 'between 850 and 900'
